<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Officials warned residents of the U.S. Virgin Islands, Puerto Rico and nearby 
islands to bolt down everything loose and stock up on food and water as 
Hurricane Dean rumbled through the eastern Caribbean. Dean was declared the 
second hurricane of the Atlantic season when winds picked up to 75 m.p.h., and 
the National Weather Center in Puerto Rico said it had strengthened to 80 
m.p.h. Hurricane warnings were posted for the Leeward Islands from Antigua to 
the U.S. Virgin Islands and Puerto Rico, said forecasters at the National 
Hurricane Center near Miami. "This is a dangerous storm and should not be taken 
lightly," an official advisory said. 
</P>
