<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: LEGAL FILE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Actor Rob Lowe's insurance company says his home and personal liability 
insurance policy doesn't cover sex tapes, and it wants a judge to free it of 
any obligation for claims if Lowe has to pay damages in a lawsuit over his 
alleged videotaping of a sex act involving a teen-age girl. Chubb Custom 
Insurance Co. of New Jersey filed a complaint in U.S. District Court in 
Atlanta, saying Lowe's policy doesn't cover "intentional actions" such as using 
"celebrity status as an inducement to females to engage in sexual intercourse, 
sodomy and multiple party sexual activity for his immediate sexual 
gratification and for the purpose of making pornographic films." ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</TEXT>
