<P>
3 COLLEGES TO GET IBM AID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Three community colleges in the area will receive more than $500,000 each in 
computer equipment and training from IBM Corp. to start a high-tech computer 
program on their campuses. 
</P>
<P>
A press briefing will be held at 10 a.m. today at the World Trade Center to 
explain the programs planned for Cerritos, El Camino and Irvine Valley 
colleges. 
</P>
<P>
The goal is to develop computer-integrated tools and techniques to keep U.S. 
manufacturing competitive. 
</P>
<P>
The three community colleges are the first in Southern California to form such 
a partnership with IBM, said Mark Wallace, Cerritos College director of 
information. Nationwide, 57 two- and four-year colleges are participating in 
the program, he said. 
